This shows the variations in the data. There seems to be some outliers - for example in sulphates total sulfur dioxide. Let’s look at the characterisitcs of a seemingly “normal” quality - alcohol.

We can see that alcohol content seems positively skewed with the most samples between 9% and 11% per volume. It would be interesting to see if the extreme cases (less than 9 or more than 11) affect quality. Let’s look at pH next.

pH seems quite normally distributed, with most values falling between 3.0 and 3.5. There seem to be some “extremes”, with some readings around 2.0 and some above 4.0! Although this relates to the summary data, this is more acidic than I was expecting (without having done any research), given that 7.0 is neutral. My intuition is that very acidic wines (less than 3.0) would negatively affect quality, so it would be good to test this.

The three acidity values seem to have different characteristics. Volatile acidity (measures acetic acid) seems to be mostly normally distributed with a slight tail to the right whilst fixed acidity (measure tartartic acid) is more skewed to the left. Citric acid (measures citric acid) is definitely skewed to the left, with most values being equal to 0. This would make a log transformation untenable. It would be interesting to explore if there is any relationship between these three characteristics. Let’s see if the square root transform to the volatile and fixed acidity produces a more normal distribution.

That seems to be more normal. Another three characteristics which could be related are the free sulphites, total sulphites and sulphates.

As I expected, the free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide data seems to have a very similar structure. The sulphates data is more normally distributed but has a tail to the right, with some extreme numbers above 1.5. Let’s look at those extremes.

There seem to be 8 instances where the sulphatesis greater than 1.5. It seems interesting that wines number 87 and 92 have exactly the same data but this could just be a very similar wine. Wine number 93 has very similar, but not the same, data. Apart from all the wines being average in quality. There does not seem to be other similar characteristics. Let’s look at the distribution of qualtiy to get a feel for if having a subset of average wine is likely.

There does not seem to be any quality ratings below three or above eight. This could be because the quality is the median of three scores, so this will inherently take away extreme cases. Given that it looks like the majority of scores are either 5 or 6, in the above subset, it does not seem unlikely we could have picked 8 random scores of 5 or 6 (although this would need to be statistically tested). The only other variables we have not looked at are chlorides, density and sugar content

It is interestnig that the residual sugar levels and chloride levels have a similar shape. Density is concentrated around 1.0, which makes sense as that is close to the density of water. The documentation says the density is related to the residual sugar content and alcohol content - it might be interesting to see if there is a relationship there.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

This dataset explores 1,599 Portuguese Vinoh Verde red wine characteristics and their quality. “X” is the ID of the wine and “Quality” is a rating from 0-10 (as assessed by the median of three wine experts), with 0 being bad and 10 being incredible. The other data is all characteristics of the wine and are all measurable quantitative qualities (as opposed to qualitative, for example flavour. Most of the wines are of a quality between 4 and 6. There seem to be some outliers in the sulpahtes, residual sugar and citric acid data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Whilst it would be ideal to be able to predict quality with some of the characteristics such as acidity or sulphate content, the limited range in the quality of the wines might limit how statistically significant this is.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

What might be more interesting is to see how different characteristics affect each other - for example, does density have anything to do with residual sugar content? Or if the different types of acidity can affect each other.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this? Yes, I took the log10 of the residual sugars and chlorides to get a less skewed and more normal distribution.

Bivariate Plots Section

Looking at all the pairs of plots (without number), most of the correlation numbers seem fairly low. In fact, the only correlation above 0.5 is citric acid to fixed acidity and total sulfuric acid to free sulfuric acid. Disappointingly, most of the qualities do not seem to correlate with quality. Alcohol content has the highest correlation of only 0.476. Most graphs seem patternless but there seems to be some sort of relationship between density and fixed acidity, and between pH and fixed acidity, which I was not expecting. There is also potentially an interesting trend in the citric acidity and density. I will take a look at these and perhaps some others to see if there are any patterns that are not apparent at first glance.

Looking at fixed.acidity versus density, we can see there is what seems to be a linear relationship, although the data seems overfitted. Some alpha was added to try see through this. There also seemed to be a relationship between citric acid and fixed acidity.

This relationship seems less clear than the density one. There could perhaps be a non- linear relationship. Let’s see if we can use a transformation to get a more linear shape.

Taking the log to base of 10 of the cube root of fixed acidity produces a more linear shape. It is also noticeable that there are bunches of data points around whole numbers, for example 0.00 and 0.50. This could suggest some inherent error in the data as I would have expected the data to be more continuous (the bunches indicates discritization). THe paper does not indicate how citric acid was physically measured but perhaps if the wine was measured with different equipment that has different levels of precision. pH also seems to affect fixed acidity so let’s look at that next.

Whilst the relationship between quality and the other characteristics seems weak, there is definitely some correlation between fixed acidity and pH, density and citrc acid so let’s try build a model.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot is interesting as it was one of the clearest indicators of quality, even though it is not actually very clear. Because of the discreteness of the quality, jitter was used to try “see” a more spread out pattern. It also demonstrates the extreme concentration of data points on wines of quality 5 and 6. It is also perhaps a reflection of what I hoped to achieve when starting this - to find a model to predict quality. What I ended up with was mostly plots like this but some clearer plots on fixed acidity!

Plot Two

Description Two

This graph shows a fairly clear relationship between pH and the log of fixed acidity and was the basis for my decision to build a linear model. The color element also shows a relationship with citric acid, which is interesting but that the more tartic acid (fixed acidity), the more citric acidity.

Plot Three

Description Three

This graphs shows a normal looking distribution of the densities of wine. It is interesting in that it is such a good example of a normal distribution! It is also interesting in that the median density is below that of water (1g/cm^3).

Reflection

Going through the data analysis of the red wine samples, I expected to focus mostly on factors that affected quality. Once I started diving into the data it became apparent that there was not a wide enough variety in the quality of wines to notice any patterns (or perhaps because of the calculation method for determining the quality a wine received).

However this led to the surprising relationship between fixed volatility and pH, density and citric acid content. It was really interesting to see the graphs evolve from 1-D to 2-D, where you can see a pattern emerging, and finally to add some color to the matter.

I would like to expand the dataset to include wines of different regions, as I think this will allow for a greater range in all the characterisitcs, which might lead to some insightful discoveries. The one thing that would also be interesting to look at, is the relationship between pH and a combination of the acidities recorded.
